3.1 Introduction: The Sensorimotor Translation Gap

The deployment of autonomous robots in unstructured, human-centric environments exposes a critical failure mode absent from simulated benchmarks: motor instability under contact uncertainty. As articulated in Problem ACT-ROBOT-2026-002, robots consistently fail not because they cannot see the world, but because they cannot translate visual intent into stable, adaptive physical action. Objects slip, delicate structures break, and performance collapses under minor environmental variations.

The core mathematical challenge is the hybrid nature of contact. Standard control laws, whether classical PID (\tau = K_p e + K_d \dot{e}) or learned policies \pi_\theta(a|s) derived from Markov Decision Processes (MDPs), assume smooth transition dynamics. Reality is defined by discontinuous jumps in system impedance—the instantaneous transition from free-space motion to rigid, frictional constraint. This chapter establishes the mathematical framework that resolves this discontinuity.

We propose Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI) , a two-timescale hybrid control architecture that couples high-frequency safety-critical control with online meta-learning. The contribution of this chapter is theoretical: we provide a formal dynamical model, a precise architectural definition, and four foundational theorems with complete proof sketches that certify the system's stability, regret, generalization, and contraction properties. No empirical data is presented; this is the mathematical blueprint upon which all subsequent algorithmic development rests.

3.2 Formal Dynamical Model: Hybrid Systems and Contact Complementarity

To reason rigorously about physical interaction, we must abandon the fiction of smooth vector fields. We model the robot-environment system as a hybrid dynamical system with state-dependent switching.

Definition 3.1 (System State).
Let the state be x = (q, \dot{q}, \lambda) \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^{2n+m}, where:

· q \in \mathbb{R}^n are generalized joint coordinates,
· \dot{q} \in \mathbb{R}^n are joint velocities,
· \lambda \in \mathbb{R}^m is the vector of contact forces (normal and tangential components).

Assumption 3.1 (Lagrangian Dynamics in Smooth Regime).
The robot obeys the standard manipulator equation away from impact events:

M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = \tau + J_c(q)^\top \lambda + d(t) \tag{3.1}

where M(q) \succ 0 is the inertia matrix, C(q,\dot{q}) is chosen to satisfy \dot{M} - 2C skew-symmetric, g(q) is gravity, J_c(q) is the contact Jacobian, \tau is control torque, and d(t) is a bounded exogenous disturbance with \|d(t)\| \leq D.

Assumption 3.2 (Contact Constraints and Filippov Regularization).
Contact forces \lambda are governed by the Signorini–Coulomb conditions. For the normal force \lambda_n:

\lambda_n \geq 0, \quad \phi_n(q) \geq 0, \quad \lambda_n \phi_n(q) = 0 \tag{3.2}

where \phi_n(q) is the signed distance to contact. For tangential force \lambda_t:

\lambda_t \in \mathcal{F}(\lambda_n), \quad \|\lambda_t\|_2 \leq \mu \lambda_n \tag{3.3}

where \mu is the friction coefficient and \mathcal{F} is the friction cone.

Because the vector field changes discontinuously at contact surfaces \Sigma = \{x \mid \phi_n(q)=0\}, we regularize using the Filippov convexification. The dynamics are extended to the differential inclusion:

\dot{x} \in \mathbf{F}(x) = \text{co}\{f_i(x) \mid i \in I(x)\} \tag{3.4}

where \{f_i\} are the vector fields from all possible contact mode combinations (e.g., sliding left, sliding right, sticking, separation). This guarantees the existence of Carathéodory solutions.

Definition 3.2 (Observation Model).
The robot receives multimodal sensory input. We assume a pre-trained cross-modal encoder \phi_\omega mapping visual and force data to a latent state z_t \in \mathbb{R}^d:

z_t = \phi_\omega(o_t), \quad o_t = [v_t^\top, f_t^\top]^\top \tag{3.5}

with bounded encoding error \mathbb{E}[\|z_t - z_t^*\|^2] \leq \epsilon_{\text{enc}}. Furthermore, we assume the availability of tactile uncertainty sets \mathcal{C}_t satisfying conformal coverage: \mathbb{P}(z_t^* \in \mathcal{C}_t) \geq 1-\alpha for a chosen significance level \alpha.

3.3 The ASI Architecture: Two-Timescale Hybrid Stochastic Control

To satisfy the constraints of millisecond-level control loops (1 kHz) and the need for online adaptation to changing contact parameters (10-100 Hz), we propose a hierarchical, two-timescale architecture. The fast loop ensures safety and stability; the slow loop updates the model of the world.

Definition 3.3 (Composite Policy).
The control torque \tau is generated by the solution of a Quadratic Program (QP) that projects a nominal learned policy onto a safe set defined by Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) and Control Barrier Functions (CBFs):

\tau = \arg\min_{a \in \mathbb{R}^n, \delta \in \mathbb{R}} \frac{1}{2}\|a - \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}}(z)\|_2^2 + \frac{\rho}{2}\delta^2 \tag{3.6}

subject to:

\dot{V}(x, a) \leq -\alpha V(x) + \delta \quad \text{(CLF Stability Constraint)} \tag{3.7}

\dot{h}(x, a) + \kappa h(x) \geq 0 \quad \text{(CBF Safety Constraint)} \tag{3.8}

where:

· \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}} is a nominal neural policy (e.g., a diffusion policy or transformer-based sequence model) trained offline on a distribution of tasks.
· V(x) is a Lyapunov function certifying convergence to a target trajectory.
· h(x) is a Barrier function defining the safe set \mathcal{C} = \{x \mid h(x) \geq 0\} (e.g., avoiding excessive force \tau_{break}).
· \delta is a relaxation variable to maintain feasibility under model error.

Assumption 3.3 (Residual Compensation).
Even with the QP safety filter, the nominal policy \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}} may fail to account for unmodeled contact dynamics (e.g., the precise friction coefficient \mu or object mass m). We augment the policy with a Lipschitz-regularized residual policy \pi_\phi^{\text{res}} that operates on the latent state and an estimated environment parameter vector \hat{\theta}_t:

\tau_{\text{final}} = \tau_{\text{QP}} + \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}(z, \hat{\theta}_t) \tag{3.9}

with the constraint \|\partial \pi_\phi^{\text{res}} / \partial x\| \leq L to prevent destabilization of the fast loop.

Definition 3.4 (Online Meta-Adaptation Law).
The slow timescale updates the internal model \hat{\theta}_t and, if necessary, the policy parameters \theta via an online meta-learning gradient step. Given a replay buffer \mathcal{D}_t of recent interaction tuples, the update is:

\theta_{t+1} = \theta_t - \eta_t \left( \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}(\theta_t; \mathcal{D}_t) + \lambda \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\text{reg}}(\theta_t, \theta_0) \right) \tag{3.10}

with a decaying step-size \eta_t = \frac{D}{G\sqrt{t}} (where G is the gradient Lipschitz constant). The regularization term \mathcal{L}_{\text{reg}} is a proximity penalty to the meta-initialized parameters \theta_0, preventing catastrophic forgetting.

The meta-training objective that produced \theta_0 is the standard MAML bi-level optimization:

\min_\theta \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{T} \sim p(\mathcal{T})} \left[ \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}}\left( \theta - \alpha \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}}(\theta) \right) \right] \tag{3.11}

where the task distribution \mathcal{T} covers variations in object mass M_i, friction \mu_i, and disturbance profiles d_i.

3.4 Theoretical Guarantees: Core Theorems and Certification

We now present the mathematical certification of the ASI architecture. These theorems provide the guarantees required for deployment in safety-critical, uncertain environments.

3.4.1 Input-to-State Stability (ISS) under Contact Disturbances

Theorem 3.1 (ISS of Hybrid ASI).
Assume:

1. The base QP (Eq. 3.6-3.8) is feasible for all x \in \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}}.
2. The residual policy is L-Lipschitz in state.
3. The exogenous disturbance is bounded \|d(t)\| \leq D.
4. Timescale separation holds: the adaptation rate \eta_t \ll 1/\text{control bandwidth}.

Then the closed-loop ASI system is Input-to-State Stable (ISS) with respect to d(t). Specifically, there exist a class \mathcal{KL} function \beta and a class \mathcal{K}_\infty function \gamma such that:

\|x(t)\| \leq \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma(D) \tag{3.12}

Proof Sketch.
Define a composite Lyapunov function candidate V_c(x, \theta) = V_{\text{CLF}}(x) + \frac{1}{2}\|\theta - \theta^*\|^2, where V_{\text{CLF}} is the Lyapunov function from the QP constraint and \theta^* is a local optimum of the adaptation loss. Using the Filippov calculus for hybrid inclusions, we evaluate the Lie derivative \dot{V}_c along the regularized dynamics.

From the QP constraint (3.7) and the skew-symmetry of \dot{M} - 2C, we have:

\dot{V}_{\text{CLF}} \leq -\alpha V_{\text{CLF}} + \gamma_1 \|d(t)\| + \gamma_2 \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\|

The Lipschitz bound on the residual and the slow variation of \theta (due to timescale separation) imply that the disturbance from the residual is bounded and can be absorbed into the \gamma(D) term. Applying the comparison lemma for differential inclusions yields the ISS bound. \square

3.4.2 Dynamic Regret of Online Adaptation

Theorem 3.2 (Dynamic Regret Bound).
Assume the online loss \ell_t(\theta) is convex and G-Lipschitz on a compact set \Theta. Assume the task drift is bounded: \|\nabla\ell_t - \nabla\ell_{t-1}\| \leq \sigma. Using decaying step size \eta_t = \frac{D}{G\sqrt{t}}, the dynamic regret satisfies:

R_T^{\text{dyn}} = \sum_{t=1}^T \ell_t(\theta_t) - \min_{\theta \in \Theta} \sum_{t=1}^T \ell_t(\theta) \leq \mathcal{O}\left( D G \sqrt{T} + \sigma T \right) \tag{3.13}

Proof Sketch.
The proof decomposes the dynamic regret into a static regret term (minimizing over a fixed comparator sequence) and a path-length penalty \sum \|\theta_{t}^* - \theta_{t-1}^*\|. Standard online gradient descent analysis bounds the static regret by O(\sqrt{T}). The meta-initialization ensures the diameter D of the search space is small relative to random initialization. The term \sigma T accounts for the non-stationarity of the environment (e.g., changing friction due to wear). Azuma-Hoeffding inequality bounds the stochastic gradient noise. \square

3.4.3 PAC-Bayes Certification for Sim-to-Real Transfer

Theorem 3.3 (Sim2Real Generalization Gap).
Let P be the prior distribution over dynamics parameters induced by simulation domain randomization. Let Q be the posterior distribution after online adaptation. Let the total variation mismatch between simulation and real dynamics be bounded by \Delta_{\text{dyn}} = \sup \|P_{\text{real}} - P_{\text{sim}}\|_{\text{TV}}. Then, with probability at least 1-\delta over the real-world samples:

\mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[R_{\text{real}}(\theta)] \leq \mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[R_{\text{sim}}(\theta)] + \sqrt{\frac{D_{\text{KL}}(Q \| P) + \log(1/\delta)}{2N}} + C \Delta_{\text{dyn}} \tag{3.14}

Proof Sketch.
This follows from the classic PAC-Bayes bound applied to the expected loss difference. The KL divergence D_{\text{KL}}(Q \| P) quantifies the information gained during online adaptation. Because P was constructed via heavy domain randomization, this divergence is naturally small (the prior covers the real distribution). The term C \Delta_{\text{dyn}} accounts for the irreducible physical discrepancy that cannot be captured by any parametric model (e.g., unmodeled flex in the links). \square

3.4.4 Exponential Contraction with Learned Residuals

Theorem 3.4 (Contraction under Lipschitz Residual).
Assume the nominal closed-loop system (QP with perfect model) is contracting in a Riemannian metric M(x) \succ 0 with rate \lambda > 0. If the Lipschitz constant L of the residual policy satisfies L < \lambda, then the augmented system contracts exponentially with rate \lambda - L:

\|x(t) - y(t)\|_M \leq e^{-(\lambda - L)t} \|x(0) - y(0)\|_M \tag{3.15}

for any two trajectories x(t), y(t).

Proof Sketch.
Consider the variational dynamics of the displacement \delta x = x - y. The presence of the residual policy modifies the Jacobian: \delta\dot{x} = (A(x) + B(x)\frac{\partial \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}}{\partial x}) \delta x. The matrix measure \mu_{M}(\cdot) of this Jacobian satisfies \mu_{M}(A + B\frac{\partial \pi}{\partial x}) \leq \mu_{M}(A) + \|B\| \|\frac{\partial \pi}{\partial x}\| \leq -\lambda + L. Integrating the bound on \frac{d}{dt}\|\delta x\|_M yields the exponential decay. \square

3.5 Architectural Design Principles Derived from the Theorems

The mathematical framework presented above is not merely descriptive; it is prescriptive. It dictates specific, verifiable design choices for the ASI architecture:

Theorem Design Mandate Verification Metric
3.1 (ISS) Mandates the QP Safety Filter. Residual policy must be Lipschitz-bounded (L < \infty). Feasibility rate of QP; Empirical Lipschitz estimate via finite differences.
3.2 (Regret) Mandates Online Meta-Update with decaying step size and replay buffer. Sublinear growth of cumulative loss on held-out interaction data.
3.3 (PAC-Bayes) Mandates Domain Randomization during offline training and KL regularization during online adaptation. KL divergence estimate between Q and P from parameter ensembles.
3.4 (Contraction) Mandates Lipschitz Regularization of the residual network (e.g., spectral normalization). Direct estimation of L via power iteration on network Jacobian.

3.6 Conclusion

This chapter has established the rigorous mathematical foundation for Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence. By modeling manipulation as a hybrid differential inclusion, we identified the precise failure modes of static control policies. We then defined the ASI architecture—a synthesis of safety-filtered QP control, online meta-learning, and Lipschitz-bounded residuals.

The four core theorems provide a certificate of correctness for this architecture. They prove that ASI is:

1. Stable (ISS despite discontinuous contacts).
2. Adaptive (Bounded dynamic regret under distribution shift).
3. Generalizable (Provable reduction of the sim-to-real gap via PAC-Bayes).
4. Contracting (Robust convergence even with unmodeled dynamics).

This theoretical scaffolding directly addresses the critical failure mode identified in ACT-ROBOT-2026-002: the inability to translate intent into stable physical action under uncertainty. The subsequent chapters of this thesis will operationalize these mathematical principles into concrete neural network architectures and algorithmic training procedures. The guarantees established herein serve as the a priori justification that such a system can, in principle, achieve robust real-world interaction.